                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><term>Monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/">Dyfed Archaeological Trust Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">2765</idno> Castle Villa (Castell Villia, Caswilia) Farm</p>
                                    <material type="stone">Quartz gabbro</material> <note>Comprised of <q>Quartz gabbro with sericite, ophitic intergrowth of clinopyroxene and plagioclase, many radiating crystals of prehnite, and chlorite pseudomorphs after olivine</q> (Edwards 2007, 286).                       </note>                                              
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                    <dimensions unit="m">
                                        <height>2.16</height>
                                        <width>0.585</width>
                                        <depth>0.48</depth>
                                    </dimensions></support>
                                <condition>The ogham inscription is very worn but clear, whereas the letters of the Latin inscription <q>are now illegible</q> (Edwards 2007, 286).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">The ogham inscription is <q>incised on the left angle of the face</q> and reads vertically upwards (Edwards 2007, 286). Macalister (1945, 399) highlighted that <q>there is no formal stem-line</q> due to the <q>rounded edge</q> of the stone. Traces of a roman-letter inscription are present on the stone in two lines, presumably reading vertically downwards.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>Macalister (1945, 399) described the inscriptions as <rs type="execution" key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs>. <height></height> 
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origPlace><placeName type="parish">Brawdy</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Pembrokeshire</placeName>, <placeName type="country">Wales</placeName>
                                <geo>51.905744, -5.077492</geo>
                            <note>National Grid Reference: SM 884 275</note></origPlace>
                            <origDate notBefore="0460" notAfter="0600" precision="low" datingMethod="#julian" evidence="linguistic">Later fifth or sixth century A.D.</origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found">The monument was in use as a footbridge when Lhuyd recorded the roman-letter inscription around 1698. The ogham inscription was not noted at this time. The ogham inscription was first noted around 1883 when the monument was rediscovered serving the same purpose in the same location, a footbridge across the Brawdy Brook on the boundary between Castle Villa Farm and Trewilym Farm. The stone was moved to the roadside near Castle Villa Farm where the roman-letter inscription was noticed in 1895. In 1896 the stone was moved to Brawdy churchyard and by 1922 it was placed in the church porch (Edwards 2007, 286).
                            <!--No ogham in Lhuyd sketches c.1698 (reproduced in RCAHMS 1925, pg 28). Slightly confused biography - might have been identified at same time as BRAW1, but reading provided by Westwood in 1884 seems incorrect; Rhys provides a reading in 1894. -->
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">In St David's Church, Brawdy lying on the east side of the porch.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
